description:
When the first frost comes along many gardeners will pack away their garden tools to get ready for winter. However, eating is an act that will continue in the cold months. During this time the body will need access to nutrient-rich vegetables that improve the immune system, ward off sickness, and keep the body healthy. In addition, cool-season greens are the sweetest greens as the cold sweetens them. 
Winter does not have to be an off-season for growing food since there are many ways to preserve outdoor plants which may not be tolerant to cold weather. Such methods can include the use of a frost cover, greenhouse, growing plants that are cold-hardy or planting in containers, and moving plants indoors when the temperature gets too low.

Every year we grow a winter garden because there are a variety of ways to grow plants during the cold months.  A major benefit to growing greens during this time of year is there are fewer pests and diseases that would otherwise make gardening difficult. 

Consider planting hardy vegetables such as collards, spinach, kale, cabbage, lettuce among other cold-tolerant crops. These are able to tolerate hard frosts usually between 25 to 28 degrees. The greens are also sweeter when planted in the cold months. If there are semi-hardy or warm crops that you'd want to grow during the winter... consider putting them in a greenhouse or plant in pots and take them indoors when the night-time temperature goes below 40 degrees Fahrenheit. 

Winter gardening is cost-effective as growing your own herbs and vegetables will save on grocery bills which are generally higher in the winter. Also, most people tend to stay indoors longer due to the cold than they would in the summer season, having a garden will get you outdoors and get some exercise. 

Regardless of whether you are new to gardening or a master gardener, determine your growing zone and choose plants accordingly. Plants that thrive in cold conditions will reward you with the best results with minimal effort.

Happy Planting.
